fields.title: Universal Search
fields.description: Get recommendations for the best sites on the web as you type in the Awesome Bar.
fields.measurements:
In addition to the [data](/privacy) collected by all Test Pilot experiments, here are the key things you should know about what is happening when you use Universal Search:

- We collect basic usage data regarding how you interact with the Awesome Bar (address bar), such as the number of characters typed, the types of results that you click, and their position in the results list.
- If you previously configured Firefox to display search suggestions in the Search Bar, installing Universal Search will enable [search suggestions](https://www.mozilla.org/privacy/firefox/#searchsuggestions) in the Awesome Bar.
- When you use the Awesome Bar, we send the terms you type to our recommendation engine. We keep anonymous logs of popular searches to improve the quality of our recommendations.
- To provide Universal Search, we use a few third-party services. We use [Bing](http://www.bing.com/developers/s/APIBasics.html) and [Yahoo](https://developer.yahoo.com/boss/search/) to provide recommendations, and [Embedly](http://docs.embed.ly/docs/) and [Clearbit](https://clearbit.com/logo) to provide additional data (such as images or icons) about those recommendations. To display the recommendations in the Awesome Bar, Universal Search may download those images directly from Embedly and Clearbit, which may allow those services to see your IP address and the image requested.

fields.introduction: Get to the best of the Web faster with Universal Search. Just type a few characters into your Awesome Bar, and the most popular sites, people and Wikipedia articles will appear for your browsing pleasure.

fields.title: Tab Center
fields.description: What would it be like to move tabs from the top of the browser to the side? We wanted to find out!
fields.measurements:
In addition to the [data](/privacy) collected by all Test Pilot experiments, here are the key things you should know about what is happening when you use Tab Center:

- We collect usage data regarding how you interact with the Tab Center, such as how often you maximize or pin Tab Center.
- We also collect information about the way you use tabs, such as the number of tabs you keep open at a time, and length of time you keep tabs open.
- Tab Center does not collect any information about sites you visit or the content of tabs.
fields._measurements_rendered:
In addition to the data collected by all Test Pilot experiments, here are the key things you should know about what is happening when you use Tab Center:

  • We collect usage data regarding how you interact with the Tab Center, such as how often you maximize or pin Tab Center.
  • We also collect information about the way you use tabs, such as the number of tabs you keep open at a time, and length of time you keep tabs open.
  • Tab Center does not collect any information about sites you visit or the content of tabs.
fields.introduction: Take your tabs from in the way to tucked away. Tab Center moves your tabs to the side of your browser window so they're out of sight when you don't need them, and easy to expand and grab when you do.
fields._introduction_rendered: Take your tabs from in the way to tucked away. Tab Center moves your tabs to the side of your browser window so they're out of sight when you don't need them, and easy to expand and grab when you do.

fields.title: Activity Stream
fields.description: A rich visual history feed and a reimagined home page make it easier than ever to find exactly what you're looking for in Firefox.
fields.measurements:
In addition to the [data](/privacy) collected by all Test Pilot experiments, here are the key things you should know about what is happening when you use Activity Stream:

- We collect basic usage data regarding how you interact with experimental new tab and timeline pages, such as the types of elements that you click and their position on the page. 
- We also collect basic information about your browser profile that affect Activity Stream, such as the number of bookmarks and history items.
- To provide Activity Stream, we fetch metadata about websites you have visited, such as images and icons, using a service called [Embedly](http://embed.ly/). We send these requests to Embedly through Mozilla’s servers, so they will not be associated with you.
fields._measurements_rendered:
In addition to the data collected by all Test Pilot experiments, here are the key things you should know about what is happening when you use Activity Stream:

  • We collect basic usage data regarding how you interact with experimental new tab and timeline pages, such as the types of elements that you click and their position on the page.
  • We also collect basic information about your browser profile that affect Activity Stream, such as the number of bookmarks and history items.
  • To provide Activity Stream, we fetch metadata about websites you have visited, such as images and icons, using a service called Embedly. We send these requests to Embedly through Mozilla’s servers, so they will not be associated with you.
fields.introduction: Get back to browsing without losing your stream of thought. Activity Stream keeps your top sites, bookmarks and recent history close at hand in each new tab. And the new timeline view gives you a birds-eye view of your browsing.

fields.copy: See where you've been, so you can get on to where you're going.
Click on a new tab, and your favorite sites are only one more click away.
Tuck away those tabs until you need them.
Pin Tab Center to see everything you've got open.
Redecorate and move the furniture! Tab Center works with your favorite Firefox themes.
Popular sites, people and Wikipedia articles appear as you type.
